## Ecosystems are living systems which each contain both a [[Unsorted/Communities\|community]] of all lifeforms in a given area, and all of the abiotic factors they rely on

### Abiotic factors
- [[Unsorted/Climate\|Climate]]
	- Temperature
	- Sunlight
	- Weather intensity
- pH
- Salinity
- [[Unsorted/Biogeochemical cycles\|Nutrient pool]] availability

## Definitions

### Population

</div></div>


<div class="transclusion internal-embed is-loaded"><div class="markdown-embed">



### Ecosystem
> A [[Unsorted/Communities\|community]] of species combined with their abiotic environment


</div></div>


- [[Unsorted/Trophic interactions\|Trophic interactions]]

## The food chain
- Based on NPP, ***Net Primary Productivity***
	- Leftover glucose (and glucose derivatives) leftover after plant respiration
	- Measured in biomass
![Pasted image 20220830182829.png|375](data:image/png;base64,)

- Often simplified into food chains
	- Primary producers, primary consumers, tertiary consumers, etc
		- Secondary, Tertiary, Quaternary
	- Basic examples
		- Plant > Herbivore > Carnivore > Carnivore
		- Phytoplankton > Zooplankton > Carnivore > Carnivore

## Decomposers
- Feed on dead producers and consumers
- Essential for the recycling of nutrients to make them available again


## Energy loss
- Only ~5-20% of energy is transfered to the next level of the food pyramid
	- ~90% loss, mainly as heat
	- Roughly 10x more biomass between every layer of a food pyramid
	- 10^(Consumer tier) * Organism mass

## Practical Applications
- Understandind food webs lets us predict how changes in an ecosystem will affect other tiers
	- Case study, Sea otters
		- Sea otters hunted to near extinction in the 1800s
			- Hunted down to ~100 members, endangered with low [[Unsorted/Biodiversity\|Biodiversity]]
		- **Food chain:**   Kelp -> Urchins -> Otters
		- Resulted in a massive spike in the sea urchin population
			- They ate nearly all the kelp
				- Died out because there was no more food
				- Everything else that relies on the kelp to survive also died out
	- Case study, Climate Change and Polar Bears
		- ![Pasted image 20220830185755.png|300](data:image/png;base64,)
- Application 2: Studying movement of toxic chemicals through the ecosystem
	- DDT is fat soluble, lingers in organism tissues
		- Does not leave the body
		- [Wikipedia Page](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/DDT)
	- DDT in water supply is taken up by algae and eaten by primary consumers
	- Concentrations massively increase in apex predators
		- High concentrations in birds of prey, damages formation of eggshells
		- ![Pasted image 20220830190600.png|275](data:image/png;base64,)
	- Banned in 1972 but persisted for decades

>How long after DDT's introduction into the environment did it start to affect the birds?


## Bioaccumulation and biomagnification
- Bioaccumulation:![Pasted image 20220902113517.png](data:image/png;base64,)
	- Accumulation of chemicals in an organism, occurs when organisms eat more of it than their bodies can naturally purge
	- Nescessary for biomagnification
- Biomagnification:
	- Increasing concentration of a substance in the tissues of organisms higher in the food chain

- Case study: Mercury in fish
	- Industrial pollution has vastly increased concentration of mercury in the environment
		- Also fat soluble, lingers in tissue
		- Gets absorbed by phytoplankton in the ocean
		- Undergoes biomagnification
			- It is now unsafe to eat fish that are high up on the food chain

## Island ecology
- Tend to have unique species
	- Small [[Unsorted/Biodiversity\|genepools]]
	- Dwarfism
- Limited survival resources
	- Small food-bearing plant [[Unsorted/Populations\|populations]] and [[Unsorted/Biodiversity\|Biodiversity]]

## Stubs

- Tropical regions get much of their water vapor from the [[Unsorted/Transpirational loss\|Transpirational loss]] of their many plants
	- Thus [[Unsorted/Deforestation\|deforestation]] reduces amount of water released into the atmosphere
	- Which can reduce the humidity of the climate, making the area unable to support a tropical ecosystem in the future

# Ecosystem Services
- Functions that healthy ecosystems provide that benefit humanity and the biosphere as a whole
- Such as:
	- Cleaning water and air
	- Cycling nutrients through the environment
		- Regulate and mediate the water cycle
	- Keeping [[Unsorted/Soil\|soils]] healthy and fertile
	- Regulate climate
	- Produce essential resources:
		- Food
		- Medicine
	- Nice habitats like forests
